  <h2>Reducible to Homogeneous Equation</h2>
  <p>For a differential equation of the form:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{ax+by+c}{a'x+b'y+c'}$$</span>
  <p>There are two primary cases to consider.</p>

  <div class="case-box">
    <h5 class="case-title">Case 1: Ratios are Unequal</h5>
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{a}{a'} \ne \frac{b}{b'}$$</span>
    <p>In this case, we use the substitutions $x = X+h$ and $y = Y+k$. This transforms the equation into a homogeneous form:</p>
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dY}{dX} = \frac{aX+bY}{a'X+b'Y}$$</span>
    <p>Which can then be solved by substituting $Y=vX$.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="case-box">
    <h5 class="case-title">Case 2: Ratios are Equal</h5>
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{b}{b'}$$</span>
    <p>Here, we use the substitution $t = ax+by$ to reduce the equation to a separable form.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <p>Solve the differential equation $(2x+3y+4)dx - (4x+6y+5)dy = 0$.</p>
    <div class="solution">
      <p>First, rewrite the equation in the standard form:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{2x+3y+4}{4x+6y+5}$$</span>
      <p>Here, $a=2, b=3, a'=4, b'=6$. We check the ratio of the coefficients:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{b}{b'} = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{1}{2}$$</span>
      <p>Since $\frac{a}{a'} = \frac{b}{b'}$, this falls under Case 2. Let's use the substitution $t = 2x+3y$.</p>
      <p>Differentiating with respect to $x$ gives:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dt}{dx} = 2 + 3\frac{dy}{dx} \implies \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{3} \left[ \frac{dt}{dx} - 2 \right]$$</span>
      <p>Now, substitute $t$ and $\frac{dy}{dx}$ back into the equation:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{1}{3} \left[ \frac{dt}{dx} - 2 \right] = \frac{t+4}{2t+5}$$</span>
      <p>Solving for $\frac{dt}{dx}$:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dt}{dx} = 3 \frac{(t+4)}{2t+5} + 2 = \frac{3t+12+4t+10}{2t+5} = \frac{7t+22}{2t+5}$$</span>
      <p>This is a variable-separable equation. We can rearrange it for integration:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{2t+5}{7t+22} dt = dx$$</span>
      <p>To integrate the left side, we use partial fraction decomposition. Let:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{2t+5}{7t+22} = A + \frac{B}{7t+22} \implies 2t+5 = A(7t+22) + B$$</span>
      <p>By comparing coefficients, $7A = 2 \implies A = \frac{2}{7}$, and $22A+B=5 \implies 22(\frac{2}{7}) + B = 5 \implies B = -\frac{9}{7}$.</p>
      <p>Now integrate:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\int \left( \frac{2}{7} - \frac{9}{7(7t+22)} \right) dt = \int dx$$</span>
      <p>The solution is:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{2}{7}t - \frac{9}{49}\ln|7t+22| = x+c$$</span>
      <p>Finally, substitute back $t = 2x+3y$ to get the general solution:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{2}{7}(2x+3y) - \frac{9}{49}\ln|7(2x+3y)+22| = x+c$$</span>
    </div>
  </div>

