  <h2>First-Order Linear DE (Leibnitz Equation)</h2>
  <p>A first-order linear differential equation has the standard form:</p>
  <div class="highlight">
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)$$</span>
    <p>where $P(x)$ and $Q(x)$ are functions of $x$.</p>
  </div>
  
  <h3>Method to Solve: Integrating Factor</h3>
  <p>We solve this by finding an **Integrating Factor (I.F.)**, denoted as $M(x)$. Multiplying the entire equation by $M(x)$ gives:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$M(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + M(x)P(x)y = M(x)Q(x)$$</span>
  <p>The goal is to make the left side the result of a product rule derivative, $\frac{d}{dx}(M(x)y) = M(x)\frac{dy}{dx} + y \frac{dM}{dx}$.</p>
  <p>By comparing the two expressions, we require $M(x)P(x)y = y \frac{dM}{dx}$, which simplifies to:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dM}{dx} = M(x)P(x)$$</span>
  <p>This is a separable equation for $M(x)$. Solving it gives the formula for the integrating factor:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\int \frac{dM}{M} = \int P(x)dx \implies \ln M(x) = \int P(x)dx$$</span>
  <div class="highlight">
    <p>The integrating factor is: $I.F. = M(x) = e^{\int P(x)dx}$.</p>
  </div>
  <p>Once the equation is multiplied by the I.F., it becomes:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\frac{d}{dx} \left[ y \cdot e^{\int P(x)dx} \right] = Q(x) e^{\int P(x)dx}$$</span>
  <p>Integrating both sides gives the final solution:</p>
  <div class="highlight">
    <span class="math-display">$$y \cdot (I.F.) = \int Q(x) \cdot (I.F.) dx + c$$</span>
  </div>

  <div class="example">
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <p>Find the particular solution of $x dy - (y-3x^2)dx = 0$ given $y(1)=2$.</p>
    <div class="solution">
      <p>Rearrange the equation into the standard linear form:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} - \frac{1}{x}y = -3x$$</span>
      <p>Here, $P(x) = -\frac{1}{x}$ and $Q(x) = -3x$.</p>
      <p>Calculate the Integrating Factor:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$I.F. = e^{\int -\frac{1}{x}dx} = e^{-\ln x} = e^{\ln x^{-1}} = x^{-1} = \frac{1}{x}$$</span>
      <p>The general solution is given by $y \cdot (I.F.) = \int Q(x) \cdot (I.F.) dx + c$:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$y \cdot \frac{1}{x} = \int (-3x) \left(\frac{1}{x}\right) dx + c$$</span>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{y}{x} = \int -3 dx = -3x + c$$</span>
      <p>The general solution is $\frac{y}{x} + 3x = c$.</p>
      <p>To find the particular solution, use the initial condition $y=2$ when $x=1$:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{2}{1} + 3(1) = c \implies c=5$$</span>
      <p>The particular solution is:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{y}{x} + 3x = 5$$</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  
