  <h2>Non-Linear Equation Reducible to Linear (Bernoulli's Equation)</h2>
  <p>A Bernoulli equation is a non-linear equation that can be transformed into a linear one. It has the standard form:</p>
  <div class="highlight">
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y = Q(x)y^n$$</span>
  </div>
  
  <h3>Solution Method</h3>
  <p>To solve, first divide the entire equation by $y^n$:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$y^{-n}\frac{dy}{dx} + P(x)y^{1-n} = Q(x)$$</span>
  <p>Next, make the substitution $z = y^{1-n}$. Differentiating this with respect to $x$ gives:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dz}{dx} = (1-n)y^{-n}\frac{dy}{dx} \implies y^{-n}\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{1-n}\frac{dz}{dx}$$</span>
  <p>Substituting these back into the transformed equation yields:</p>
  <span class="math-display">$$\frac{1}{1-n}\frac{dz}{dx} + P(x)z = Q(x)$$</span>
  <p>Multiplying by $(1-n)$ gives a first-order linear DE in $z$:</p>
  <div class="highlight">
    <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dz}{dx} + (1-n)P(x)z = (1-n)Q(x)$$</span>
  </div>
  <p>This can now be solved using the integrating factor method.</p>

  <div class="example">
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <p>Solve $x \frac{dy}{dx} + y = x^2 y^6$.</p>
    <div class="solution">
      <p>First, divide by $x$ to get the standard Bernoulli form:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{1}{x}y = x^2 y^6$$</span>
      <p>Here, $n=6$. Divide by $y^6$:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{1}{y^6}\frac{dy}{dx} + \frac{1}{xy^5} = x^2$$</span>
      <p>Let $z = y^{1-6} = y^{-5}$. Then $\frac{dz}{dx} = -5y^{-6}\frac{dy}{dx}$, which means $\frac{1}{y^6}\frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{1}{5}\frac{dz}{dx}$.</p>
      <p>Substitute to get an equation in terms of $z$:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$-\frac{1}{5}\frac{dz}{dx} + \frac{1}{x}z = x^2$$</span>
      <p>Multiply by -5 to get the linear form:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$\frac{dz}{dx} - \frac{5}{x}z = -5x^2$$</span>
      <p>The new $P(x)$ is $-\frac{5}{x}$. The Integrating Factor is:</p>
      <span class="math-display">$$I.F. = e^{\int -\frac{5}{x}dx} = e^{-5\ln x} = e^{\ln x^{-5}} = \frac{1}{x^5}$$</span>
      <p>The equation can now be solved for $z$ and then converted back to $y$.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>